#: ../../source/how_does_it_work/abstraction_layer.rst:3
msgid ""
"Because ``Charmy GUI`` supports `multiple backend and frontend "
"libraries`, we need to ``abstract`` their methods so they can switch "
"between them at any time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/how_does_it_work/abstraction_layer.rst:6
msgid ""
"So we can use the map method to map the methods of the backend library to"
" the methods of the frontend library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/how_does_it_work/abstraction_layer.rst:12
msgid ""
"Then, by checking whether a certain library is installed, add the mapping"
" method. Let's use create() as an example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/how_does_it_work/abstraction_layer.rst:24
msgid "It's the same for other libraries as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/how_does_it_work/abstraction_layer.rst:36
msgid ""
"Then, we can execute the corresponding framework's methods through the "
"mapping table and the selected framework name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/how_does_it_work/abstraction_layer.rst:43
msgid ""
"That's the principle of the abstraction layer. Next, you can delve deeper"
" through the source code and testing."
msgstr ""

